english:
  title: On Gyeongchun
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    During my travels through the Eastern region, the magistrate of Ganseong, Park Gun, sought a courtesy name and asked me to compose words of meaning. I am old now—my learning has grown dim, my brush uncertain. Words flow but form no pattern; meanings rise but never touch their depths. How can I bear such responsibility? And yet we shared the same monastery walls in days past, so we cannot be strangers. Since he now seeks me out with such earnest heart, I cannot refuse him.

    Thus I name him Gyeongchun and speak these words: "Benevolence in Heaven is Life; in Man it is Heart. The character Eul in direction dwells in the East; in things, it dwells in Wood. Therefore Benevolence encompasses the Four Virtues, and Eul crowns the Four Directions—it is the way the Celestial Emperor emerges and moves through the turning year. When it moves eastward, we call it Spring; southward, Summer; westward, Autumn; northward, Winter. Winter returns again to Spring, and life begets life without end. Ten thousand ages are as a single day. That Spring crowns the four seasons is no falsehood; that Benevolence embraces the Four Virtues is no empty claim. What more need be said of the meaning of Eul?

    In humankind, to nurture the heart is Benevolence. In the home, it blooms as love and filial piety; in governance, as compassion for suffering. This is Benevolence unfolding. When one's countenance grows pure and serene, when the back grows full and the heart expands, when the body takes on vigor—this is Benevolence manifesting, Spring's radiance shining forth. The people, following this transformation, stand in the spring breeze. Warm currents flow in all directions, spreading to the infinite horizons. How much more so in a single province? When one rises to position through virtue, spreading benevolence as the gentle rains of spring—is this not the natural way? Fix your mind upon this path.
  footnotes:
    - Gyeongchun (景春) is a courtesy name formed through wordplay on the recipient's name and Neo-Confucian philosophy. The name suggests both 'spring scenery' and embodies virtues associated with benevolence and the East.
    - The Eastern region (關東) refers to the territories east of the capital in Goryeo.
    - 'Lee Saek employs traditional Five Elements correlations: the East corresponds to the Spring season and Wood, associated with growth and benevolence (仁).'
    - The reference to 'standing in the spring breeze' alludes to Mencius' teaching that virtuous governance influences people naturally and effortlessly.
